⏺ You mentioned the "Checkout" section from guide.md, but it appears it wasn't included in your message. Let me modify the approach based on my understanding of rrweb's "Checkout"
  functionality.

  Rrweb's "Checkout" feature creates a full snapshot of the page state at regular intervals, which is important for:
  1. Properly initializing replay from any point in time
  2. Keeping the snapshot that's needed when we only want to send the last 5 minutes of recording

  Let me update the approach to use this feature more effectively:

  // src/browser/replay/recorder.js
  import * as record from '@rrweb/record';

  export class ReplayRecorder {
    constructor(options = {}) {
      this.options = {
        // Default replay options
        checkoutEveryNms: 300000, // Take full snapshot every 5 minutes
        blockClass: 'rr-block',
        maskTextClass: 'rr-mask',
        maskInputs: true,
        recordCanvas: false,
        // Time buffer in milliseconds (5 minutes = 300000ms)
        bufferDuration: 300000,
        // Override with user options
        ...options
      };

      this.events = [];
      this.startTime = null;
      this.stopFn = null;
      this.isRecording = false;
      this.lastCheckoutTime = 0;
    }

    start() {
      if (this.isRecording) return;

      this.startTime = Date.now();
      this.events = [];
      this.lastCheckoutTime = this.startTime;

      this.stopFn = record.record({
        emit: event => {
          // The timestamp is already included in the event by rrweb
          this.events.push(event);

          // Use rrweb's checkout mechanism to create snapshots at intervals
          if (event.type === 2 && (Date.now() - this.lastCheckoutTime > this.options.checkoutEveryNms)) {
            record.checkout();
            this.lastCheckoutTime = Date.now();
          }

          this._pruneOldEvents();
        },
        checkoutEveryNms: this.options.checkoutEveryNms,
        ...this.options
      });

      this.isRecording = true;
      return this;
    }

    // When getting the last 5 minutes, ensure we include the most recent full snapshot
    getLastNMinutes(minutes) {
      const timeThreshold = Date.now() - (minutes * 60 * 1000);

      // Find the most recent full snapshot event (type = 2)
      let lastSnapshotIndex = this.events.findIndex(event =>
        event.type === 2 && event.timestamp < timeThreshold
      );

      // If no snapshot found before the time threshold, use the first event
      if (lastSnapshotIndex === -1) lastSnapshotIndex = 0;

      // Return the snapshot and all events after the time threshold
      return this.events.slice(lastSnapshotIndex).filter(event =>
        event.timestamp >= timeThreshold || event.type === 2
      );
    }

    // Other methods remain the same
    // ...

    // Modified pruning method to keep at least one full snapshot
    _pruneOldEvents() {
      if (this.events.length <= 1) return;

      const threshold = Date.now() - this.options.bufferDuration;

      // Find the last full snapshot before the threshold
      let lastSnapshotIndex = -1;
      for (let i = this.events.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        if (this.events[i].type === 2 && this.events[i].timestamp < threshold) {
          lastSnapshotIndex = i;
          break;
        }
      }

      // If no snapshot found, keep the first event which should be a full snapshot
      if (lastSnapshotIndex === -1) lastSnapshotIndex = 0;

      // Keep the snapshot and events after the threshold
      this.events = this.events.slice(lastSnapshotIndex).filter(event =>
        event.timestamp >= threshold || event.type === 2
      );
    }
  }

  This updated implementation:

  1. Uses rrweb's built-in checkout mechanism to create snapshots regularly
  2. Ensures we always keep the most recent snapshot, even if it's older than the buffer window
  3. Makes sure that when retrieving recordings, we always include the necessary snapshot to properly reconstruct the DOM state
  4. Uses event types provided by rrweb instead of assuming structure

  The approach now properly leverages rrweb's built-in features for event timestamps and checkpoints, making the integration more robust.

> But see, this is still wrong. Here is what the documentation says: Checkout

  By default, all the emitted events are required to replay a session and if you do not want to store all the events, you can use the checkout config.

  **Most of the time you do not need to configure this**. But if you want to do something like capturing just the last N events from when an error has occurred, here is an example:

  ```js
  // We use a two-dimensional array to store multiple events array
  const eventsMatrix = [[]];

  rrweb.record({
    emit(event, isCheckout) {
      // isCheckout is a flag to tell you the events has been checkout
      if (isCheckout) {
        eventsMatrix.push([]);
      }
      const lastEvents = eventsMatrix[eventsMatrix.length - 1];
      lastEvents.push(event);
    },
    checkoutEveryNth: 200, // checkout every 200 events
  });

  // send last two events array to the backend
  window.onerror = function () {
    const len = eventsMatrix.length;
    const events = eventsMatrix[len - 2].concat(eventsMatrix[len - 1]);
    const body = JSON.stringify({ events });
    fetch('http://YOUR_BACKEND_API', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      },
      body,
    });
  };
  ```

  Due to the incremental-snapshot-chain mechanism rrweb used, we can not capture the last N events accurately. With the sample code above, you will finally get the last 200 to 400 events
  been sent to your backend.

  Similarly, you can also configure `checkoutEveryNms` to capture the last N minutes events:

  ```js
  // We use a two-dimensional array to store multiple events array
  const eventsMatrix = [[]];

  rrweb.record({
    emit(event, isCheckout) {
      // isCheckout is a flag to tell you the events has been checkout
      if (isCheckout) {
        eventsMatrix.push([]);
      }
      const lastEvents = eventsMatrix[eventsMatrix.length - 1];
      lastEvents.push(event);
    },
    checkoutEveryNms: 5 * 60 * 1000, // checkout every 5 minutes
  });

  // send last two events array to the backend
  window.onerror = function () {
    const len = eventsMatrix.length;
    const events = eventsMatrix[len - 2].concat(eventsMatrix[len - 1]);
    const body = JSON.stringify({ events });
    fetch('http://YOUR_BACKEND_API', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      },
      body,
    });
  };
  ```

  With the sample code above, you will finally get the last 5 to 10 minutes of events been sent to your backend.

