> Why "options.replay.enabled === false" and not simply "!options.replay.enabled"? Does this have to do with enabled being null or undefined?

⏺ Yes, exactly. This is to handle the difference between enabled: false specifically set versus when enabled isn't defined at all.

  - options.replay.enabled === false: This checks if enabled is explicitly set to false (strict equality)
  - !options.replay.enabled: This would evaluate to true when enabled is false, null, undefined, 0, '', or NaN

  I used the strict equality check because we only want to stop and nullify the recorder when the user explicitly sets enabled to false, rather than when the property is just not defined
  or has some falsy value.

  This allows for configurations where the user might not specify the enabled property at all in the configure call, but still wants to keep the existing recorder state.

  Would you like me to use a different approach for this check?

